# Auth Service Platform – Full Technical Breakdown

> Purpose: This document defines **what we are building**, **why it exists**, **who it serves**, and **how the codebase is structured**, so development can start immediately and tools like GitHub Copilot have full context.

---

## 1. The Core Problem We Are Solving

Most developers waste **weeks** rebuilding the same boring but critical infrastructure:

* Email + password auth
* Social login
* Token handling
* Email verification
* Password resets
* Basic user management

Frameworks like Django *help*, but:

* They are framework-locked
* They are not productized
* They don’t work cleanly across stacks
* They don’t scale across organizations

**We are building a reusable, framework-agnostic authentication platform** that:

* Can be used internally by startups
* Can be embedded into customer-facing apps
* Does *not* force teams to design auth from scratch

Think **"Stripe for authentication primitives"**, but leaner and more opinionated.

---

## 2. Who This Is For (Very Important)

We are **not** targeting:

* Complex enterprise RBAC systems
* Banks
* Government systems
* Massive multi-tenant IAM products

We **are** targeting:

* Solo founders
* Early-stage startups
* Indie hackers
* Small teams
* Products with *simple onboarding needs*

If someone says:

> “I don’t want to think about auth anymore”

They are our customer.

---

## 3. How People Use This (3 Clear Modes)

### Mode 1: Internal Auth (B2B Startup Use)

A company uses this **only for their own product**.

* They create an organization
* They generate API keys
* Their backend talks to us
* Their frontend never touches auth logic

Example:

* SaaS dashboard
* Admin panels
* MVPs

---

### Mode 2: Embedded Auth (Customer-Facing Apps)

A company uses our auth system **for their users**.

* Users sign up through our endpoints
* Tokens are issued by us
* The company consumes user identity

We handle:

* Registration
* Login
* Email verification
* Password resets

They handle:

* Business logic

---

### Mode 3: Self-Hosted (Open-Core)

Developers can:

* Clone the repo
* Deploy it themselves
* Modify it

But:

* **Hosted features** (rate limits, analytics, email infra, dashboards) are paid
* Self-hosted version is community-supported

This protects us from "someone cloning and reselling".

---

## 4. Monetization Strategy (Clear + Defensible)

We monetize **services**, not code.

### Free Tier

* Limited requests/month
* Basic email/password
* Community support

### Paid Tier

* Higher rate limits
* Social auth providers
* Webhooks
* Audit logs
* SLA

### Enterprise / Custom

* Custom domains
* Dedicated instances
* Compliance

Open code ≠ open business.

---

## 5. Public API Contract (High-Level)

### Authentication Endpoints

```
POST   /v1/auth/register
POST   /v1/auth/login
POST   /v1/auth/logout
POST   /v1/auth/refresh
```

### User Management

```
GET    /v1/users/me
PATCH  /v1/users/me
DELETE /v1/users/me
```

### Password & Email

```
POST /v1/auth/password/reset-request
POST /v1/auth/password/reset-confirm
POST /v1/auth/email/verify
```

### Organization & Keys

```
POST /v1/orgs
GET  /v1/orgs/:id
POST /v1/orgs/:id/keys
```

Auth is always **token-based**.

---

---

## 7. Why Django Is the Right Starting Point

We leverage Django **internally**, but expose a **clean HTTP API**.

Benefits:

* Django auth for speed
* Django Allauth for social login
* Django REST Framework for APIs
* JWT instead of sessions

Users of the platform **never depend on Django**.

---

## 8. Security Model

* Short-lived access tokens
* Refresh tokens
* Per-org API keys
* Hashing with modern standards
* Rate limiting by key + IP

No shortcuts here.

---

## 9. What Happens After “Code Is Ready”

1. Deploy hosted version
2. Publish docs
3. Release SDKs (JS first)
4. Launch free tier
5. Onboard first startups manually

We do **not** chase scale immediately.

---

## 10. Naming Direction (Temporary)

HVT is a placeholder.

We want something:

* Tactical
* Infrastructure-sounding
* Memorable


---

## 11. Final Positioning Statement

> “We remove authentication from your list of problems.”

That’s the whole product.

